*RP* The Initiate Seeks to become a Disciple.<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
The young prophet looked over his latest acquisition. The potions he had acquired from the Ebon Mask had done their job - the young Silverstar slept soundly. As he gathered the tools he would require for the upcoming experiments, there was a knock at the door. He went to answer and discovered one of his contacts in the commons. The man was very devout, and had been following the sermons of the young prophet for some time. Every once in a while, he provided some information that he thought the young prophet might find useful. &quot;Yes child, what can I do for you tonight?&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;I have information for you in regards to the one named Xosha X'Tai.&quot; <br>
<br>
Pravdameer had let it be known he was seeking some information on certain things and people, and the young assassin was one of them - he had a job that would require her expertise, but until now he had been unable to find her. &quot;Yes, child? Continue.&quot; <br>
<br>
The man nodded from the shadows and said, &quot;She has been seen in the city again - at the Blind Fish. She will not be there long, but will most likely depart again for more travels.&quot; <br>
<br>
The young prophet nodded and then gave the man the blessings of the Father as he said, &quot;Go now with the power that True Hatred gives, child&quot; The man thanked the young priest for his gift and then hurried off. Pravdameer turned then to seemingly thin air and said, &quot;Well, it seems the time has come, Atoxus. I must speak with this assassin and gain her aid in order to finish the last stage of the task given me to attain the rank of Disciple of Hatred. It should prove...interesting. I wonder just how much she knows of me - and how much I have yet to learn of her. Yes, I know that Atoxus - I was a member of the Shadows of the Blade after all. Yes, I also heard she was associated with House W'Rath, but that is not as much a strike against her as it would be if she were associated with the Traitor. You can't be serious? She is friendly with that one?&quot; <br>
<br>
The young Prophet of Hate smiled a bone-chilling grin as he thought back on his history with that one. &quot;I wonder if she has learned yet that she failed to remove me from the lands of Norrath? Most likely.&quot; The Prophet then looked back at the unconscious form lying on the slab. &quot;Ironic that I should be dealing with a friend of the rogue and a member of her former house at the same time. Granted, this bard is no ranger, but then, our task is not the same this time either. We do not have much time, so I will go to the Fish and approach the young assassin, and then return here to see if I can learn what I need to in order to tend to the issue.&quot; <br>
<br>
Pravdameer nodded, and then secured the door to his chambers within the halls of the Violent Harvest and headed for the Blind Fish. <br>
<br>
As he entered the bar, he saw her sitting at a table looking out the window seemingly absorbed in thought about something or other. Pravdameer approached her table cautiously - he didn't want to startle the young assassin. He was but a few steps away when she said, just under her breath, &quot;It's about time you arrived Priest. I was beginning to wonder how blatant I would have to be before you came out to see me. I understand you have been looking for me?&quot; <br>
<br>
Pravdameer quickly suppressed his surprise, and merely said, &quot;Yes - I understand your services are available. I seek to work with you as a fellow member of the Violent Harvest to eliminate some ankle biter spies from within our fair city. I do not believe I am up to the task alone, as I am a man of peace, not war - I am a healer, not a warrior.&quot; The young prophet smirked at the half-truth of his words, pulled out a bottle of his personal stock of Fish Wine, and poured a glass for each. &quot;I would be happy to answer any questions you might have, child.&quot; He saw a glimpse of the fires of hate flare up as he called her child, and couldn't help but chuckle as he awaited her answer. <br>
<br>
