Re: *RP* The Initiate Seeks to become a Disciple.<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Xosha had been restocking for sometime now. The missive she had received from Selilya having been put off too long, she had decided to get started with the attempt on the Erudite in Kerra Isle. <br>
<br>
She hadn't the least idea where it was, or who this woman was, and what her unholy discrepincy against the Tier'Dal of the Violent Harvest might have been. But truly it mattered not. This killing would be the first step in a long ladder of personal and social assencion fro Xosha, and with her Mentor behind her (Innoruuk keep her soul) and having reunited with her friends a few times, the time had come to start that ascension. <br>
<br>
And so it was the Xosha bartered at the counter in the commons with a food peddler. She sighed and payed the hefty some for a weeks worth of rations and water. The merchant keeping a warry eye on her all the while. <br>
<br>
&quot;Relax, I told you I'm not with the Ebon Mask anymore, it's been years, really!&quot; Xosha sighed. <br>
<br>
&quot;All the same rogue,&quot; he spat the words out, &quot;I shall keep my eye on you as you back out, no funny business!&quot; <br>
<br>
Again Xosha sighed. This was really a pain in the ass, it was as if there was some master list of all inductees of her field that circled around the- <br>
<br>
Out of the corner of her eye Xosha saw a small figure, not dressed dark, but rather dressed too plain. Dressed as if to mix in well with the crowd. Unfortunately the manner inwhich he watched her was all wrong, he stood in one place too long, then at Xosha's glance, would turn and talk casually to a vendor, a vendor who would inturn look a little puzzled at the sudden informality. <br>
<br>
Xosha smiled to herself, no, not a killer. Sure Xosha was next to unseen in Neriak nowadays, she doubted there would be any action against her. The gain from killing a little rogue like herself could be only minor, say the coins in her pocket. She would expect agression against her in the dirty streets at Foreign Quarter from the standard ruffians, but certainly not spying. <br>
<br>
Xo walked calmly out of the food shop, and nodded politely to the vendor as a goodbye. He snarled back at her as his farewell. Then she walked to the Blind Fish, took up a booth, ordered Elven Wine, and waited. <br>
<br>
It was a member of her prospective guild that finally approached her. Pradameer, she thought to herself. The name had always been a familiar one to her, something in it ringed of anger and maybe even of treachory. She thought she might need to dislike this one for her past, but try as she might, she could not conjure the reasons why, and so then dismissed it as foolishness. <br>
<br>
She smiled to him and nodded, he smiled to her and did the same, then took a seat and did not order. <br>
<br>
&quot;Lady X'Tai,&quot; he grinned. Pravdameer had a beautiful set of teeth, she thought. It did tend to make is mouth look a tad too menacing though. <br>
<br>
&quot;Prav,&quot; she referred to him informall, on purpose. &quot;I have been expecting you.&quot; <br>
<br>
And thus the gentle parlay and interchange of attack, counter attack, riposte, parry, dodge that would be thier conversation ensued. <br>
<br>
Eventually Xosha was a bit taken aback. This one needed a piece of work done. Surely this cocky finger waggler didn't need her services? She was forced to revaluate her subject. The noted first the newness of his garb. When first she had seen him she picked it up as him wanting to just look good, but now she thought maybe it was new because he hadn't seen enough action to make it old and worn. His face, free of scarring, his staff, only slightly dented. He was wealthy enough to afford a spy, but not the kind of wealth that someone out in Norrath would find killing dragons. <br>
<br>
He ended the conversation with the almost typical now &quot;child&quot; reference. Xosha barred her teeth immediately, and Prav smiled. No, thought Xosha, if he calls me child, it is certainly not due to my station among assassins. I think THIS one calls everyone child. Xosha could feel his burning hate almost across the table. It was likely he called everyone child in an attempt to anger, and in anger somehow lead them to hating him... very tricky this one. <br>
<br>
Xosha leaned back, quieted her face and her body as she had been taught. Extended her palm, spat into it and said, &quot;That'll be five hundred platinum a head Prav,&quot; then cocked her lip in a sneer. <br>
<br>
The magic caster followed suit, spitting in his and clasping hers. <br>
<br>
If nothing better, I am one step deeper into this guild, she thought. Next I think I'll be meeting thier Selilya. Soon as I kill this fool Erudite. <br>
<br>
Xosha bought another round, offered Pravdameer a drink, he smiled politely and shook his head no, Xosha shrugged, and drank.  <br>
